Here is a concise, step‐by‐step solution.

(a)  Two successive Doppler shifts occur: first the moving bat (source) and moving insect (observer), then the moving insect (now source) and moving bat (observer).

1.  Bat→insect:  
   Let the sound speed be \(v\), the bat’s speed \(v_{\rm bat}\) (toward the insect), the insect’s speed \(v_{\rm in}\) (toward the bat), and the emitted frequency \(f_{\rm bat}\).  Then the frequency heard by the insect is
   \[
     f_1 \;=\; f_{\rm bat}\,\frac{v + v_{\rm in}}{\,v - v_{\rm bat}\,}\,.
   \]

2.  Insect→bat (reflection):  
   The insect re‐emits at frequency \(f_1\) in its rest frame; viewed by the bat (moving at \(v_{\rm bat}\)), the reflected frequency is
   \[
     f_{\rm refl}
     \;=\;
     f_1\,\frac{v + v_{\rm bat}}{\,v - v_{\rm in}\,}
     \;=\;
     f_{\rm bat}\,
     \frac{v + v_{\rm in}}{v - v_{\rm bat}}\,
     \frac{v + v_{\rm bat}}{v - v_{\rm in}}\,.
   \]

3.  Solve for \(v_{\rm in}\).  Set
   \[
     \frac{f_{\rm refl}}{f_{\rm bat}}
     =\frac{(v+v_{\rm in})(v+v_{\rm bat})}{(v-v_{\rm bat})(v-v_{\rm in})}
   \]
   and, after clearing denominators and isolating \(v_{\rm in}\), one obtains
   \[
     \boxed{
     v_{\rm in}
     \;=\;
     v\,
     \frac{\,f_{\rm refl}\,(v - v_{\rm bat})
            \;-\;
            f_{\rm bat}\,(v + v_{\rm bat})\,}
          {\,f_{\rm refl}\,(v - v_{\rm bat})
            \;+\;
            f_{\rm bat}\,(v + v_{\rm bat})\,}
     }.
   \]

(b)  Numerical substitution.  Take
   \[
     f_{\rm bat}=80.7\times10^3\rm\,Hz,\quad
     f_{\rm refl}=83.5\times10^3\rm\,Hz,\quad
     v_{\rm bat}=3.9\rm\,m/s,\quad
     v=343\rm\,m/s.
   \]
   Then
   \[
     v_{\rm in}
     \approx
     \frac{343\bigl[83.5\times10^3\,(343-3.9)\;-\;80.7\times10^3\,(343+3.9)\bigr]}
          {\,83.5\times10^3\,(343-3.9)\;+\;80.7\times10^3\,(343+3.9)\,}
     \approx1.95\rm\ m/s.
   \]

Final Answers (brief):

(a)  
\[
v_{\rm in}
=
v\,
\frac{f_{\rm refl}(v - v_{\rm bat}) - f_{\rm bat}(v + v_{\rm bat})}
     {f_{\rm refl}(v - v_{\rm bat}) + f_{\rm bat}(v + v_{\rm bat})}\,.
\]

(b)  \(v_{\rm in}\approx1.95\rm\ m/s.\)

Here is the detailed solution followed by a brief summary of the final answers.

1. Gravitational force between electron and positron  
   \[
     F_{g} \;=\; \frac{G\,m_{e}\,m_{e}}{r^{2}}
            \;=\; \frac{G\,m_{e}^{2}}{r^{2}}
   \]
   where  
   • \(G\) is the gravitational constant (\(6.67\times10^{-11}\,\mathrm{m^{3}kg^{-1}s^{-2}}\)),  
   • \(m_{e}\) is the electron mass (\(9.11\times10^{-31}\,\mathrm{kg}\)).

2. Electric (Coulomb) force of attraction between electron and positron  
   \[
     F_{e} \;=\; \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\;\frac{e^{2}}{r^{2}}
            \;=\; k\,\frac{e^{2}}{r^{2}}
   \]
   where  
   • \(\varepsilon_{0}=8.85\times10^{-12}\,\mathrm{F/m}\),  
   • \(k=1/(4\pi\varepsilon_{0})\approx8.99\times10^{9}\,\mathrm{N\,m^{2}/C^{2}}\),  
   • \(e=1.60\times10^{-19}\,\mathrm{C}\).

3. Ratio of gravitational to electric force  
   \[
     \frac{F_{g}}{F_{e}}
     \;=\;
     \frac{\displaystyle \frac{G\,m_{e}^{2}}{r^{2}}}
          {\displaystyle k\,\frac{e^{2}}{r^{2}}}
     \;=\;
     \frac{G\,m_{e}^{2}}{k\,e^{2}}
     \;=\;
     \frac{G\,m_{e}^{2}\,4\pi\varepsilon_{0}}{e^{2}}.
   \]

4. Numerical estimate  
   \[
     \frac{F_{g}}{F_{e}}
     \;\approx\;
     \frac{(6.67\times10^{-11})(9.11\times10^{-31})^{2}}
          {(8.99\times10^{9})(1.60\times10^{-19})^{2}}
     \;\sim\; 10^{-43}.
   \]

5. Physical conclusion  
   Since \(\displaystyle F_{g}/F_{e}\sim10^{-43}\), the gravitational attraction between an electron and positron is utterly negligible compared to their electric attraction.  
   In bubble‐chamber (and other particle‐detector) experiments, one can safely ignore gravitational forces and consider only electromagnetic (and other non‐gravitational) interactions.

––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––––  
