Below is a step‐by‐step solution.  In all expressions we take the pipe inner radius  
\(r_i=\tfrac{D_i}{2}=0.0125\rm\;m\), pipe outer radius  
\(r_o=\tfrac{D_o}{2}=0.015\rm\;m\), insulation outer radius  
\(r_2=r_o+0.025=0.040\rm\;m\), and length \(L=10\rm\;m.\)

1)  Define the four thermal resistances in series:

   a)  Inner convection (fluid → pipe wall)  
      \[
        R_{\rm conv,i}
        \;=\;\frac{1}{h_i\,A_i}
        \;=\;\frac{1}{h_i\,(2\pi r_iL)}
        \;=\;\frac1{150\,(2\pi\cdot0.0125\cdot10)}
        \;=\;8.488\times10^{-3}\;\rm K/W.
      \]

   b)  Conduction through the steel pipe wall  
      \[
        R_{\rm pipe}
        \;=\;\frac{\ln(r_o/r_i)}{2\pi k_{\rm pipe}L}
        \;=\;\frac{\ln(0.015/0.0125)}{2\pi\,(14)\,(10)}
        \;=\;2.07\times10^{-4}\;\rm K/W.
      \]

   c)  Conduction through the insulation (thermal conductivity \(k_{\rm ins}\))  
      \[
        R_{\rm ins}
        \;=\;\frac{\ln(r_2/r_o)}{2\pi\,k_{\rm ins}\,L}
        \;=\;\frac{\ln(0.040/0.015)}{2\pi\,k_{\rm ins}\,(10)}.
      \]

   d)  Outer convection (pipe surface → ambient)  
      \[
        R_{\rm conv,o}
        \;=\;\frac{1}{h_o\,A_o}
        \;=\;\frac{1}{25\,(2\pi\,0.040\cdot10)}
        \;=\;1.591\times10^{-2}\;\rm K/W.
      \]

2)  Total resistance from fluid to ambient is
   \[
     R_{\rm tot}
     = R_{\rm conv,i}+R_{\rm pipe}+R_{\rm ins}+R_{\rm conv,o}.
   \]

3)  If \(T_{\rm fluid}=135^\circ\!C\) and \(T_{\rm amb}=20^\circ\!C\), the heat rate is
   \[
     \dot Q
     =\frac{T_{\rm fluid}-T_{\rm amb}}{R_{\rm tot}}\,.
   \]
   We require the outside surface temperature 
   \(\displaystyle T_{s,out}=T_{\rm amb}+\dot Q\,R_{\rm conv,o}\le45^\circ\!C.\)

4)  Enforce \(T_{s,out}=45^\circ\!C\).  Then
   \[
    \dot Q
    =\frac{45-20}{R_{\rm conv,o}}
    =\frac{25}{R_{\rm conv,o}}
    \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
    \frac{25}{R_{\rm conv,o}}
    =\frac{135-20}{R_{\rm tot}}\,.
   \]
   Hence
   \[
     R_{\rm tot}
     =\frac{115}{25}\;R_{\rm conv,o}
     =4.6\,R_{\rm conv,o}
     =4.6\,(1.591\times10^{-2})
     =7.32\times10^{-2}\;\rm K/W.
   \]
   Thus
   \[
     R_{\rm ins}
     =R_{\rm tot}-R_{\rm conv,i}-R_{\rm pipe}-R_{\rm conv,o}
     =7.32\times10^{-2}
       -8.488\times10^{-3}
       -2.07\times10^{-4}
       -1.591\times10^{-2}
     =4.858\times10^{-2}\;\rm K/W.
   \]

5)  Finally solve for \(k_{\rm ins}\):
   \[
     k_{\rm ins}
     =\frac{\ln(r_2/r_o)}{2\pi\,L\,R_{\rm ins}}
     =\frac{\ln(0.040/0.015)}{2\pi\,(10)\,(4.858\times10^{-2})}
     \approx0.32\;\rm W/(m\cdot K).
   \]

Answer in brief:

• Required maximum thermal conductivity of the 2.5 cm insulation is  
  \(k_{\rm ins}\le0.32\rm\;W/m\cdot K\).  
• With this \(k_{\rm ins}\), the outer surface temperature will be \(45^\circ\!C\).  
• The total heat loss is \(\dot Q=(45-20)/R_{\rm conv,o}\approx1.57\rm\;kW\) over the 10 m pipe.

Here is a step‐by‐step solution:

1.  Magnetic field of a long, straight current  
    For a long straight wire carrying current \(I\), the magnetic field at distance \(r\) is
    \[
      B \;=\;\frac{\mu_0\,I}{2\pi\,r},
      \quad
      \mu_0 = 4\pi\times10^{-7}\,\mathrm{T\cdot m/A}.
    \]

2.  (a)  Lightning bolt: \(I=2.0\times10^4\) A, \(r=5\) m  
    \[
      B_{\rm light}
      = \frac{(4\pi\times10^{-7}\,\mathrm{T\,m/A})\,(2.0\times10^4\,\mathrm{A})}
             {2\pi\,(5\,\mathrm{m})}
      = \frac{8\pi\times10^{-3}}{10\pi}
      = 8.0\times10^{-4}\,\mathrm{T}
      = 0.80\,\mathrm{mT}.
    \]

3.  (b)  Household wire: \(I=10\) A, \(r=0.05\) m  
    \[
      B_{\rm house}
      = \frac{(4\pi\times10^{-7})\,(10)}{2\pi\,(0.05)}
      = \frac{4\pi\times10^{-6}}{0.1\pi}
      = 4.0\times10^{-5}\,\mathrm{T}
      = 0.040\,\mathrm{mT}.
    \]

4.  Comparison:  
    \[
      \frac{B_{\rm light}}{B_{\rm house}}
      = \frac{8.0\times10^{-4}}{4.0\times10^{-5}}
      = 20.
    \]
    So the lightning field at 5 m is about 20 times larger.

Final Answers (brief)

(a) \(B_{\rm light}\approx8.0\times10^{-4}\,\mathrm{T}=0.80\,\mathrm{mT}.\)  
(b) \(B_{\rm house}\approx4.0\times10^{-5}\,\mathrm{T}=0.040\,\mathrm{mT}.\)  
Lightning’s field is about 20 × that of the household wire at the given distances.

