(1) \(T^2=\dfrac{4\pi^2}{GM}\,r^3\).  
For the exoplanet (subscript p) and the Earth (subscript e), divide the two instances of (1):  
\[
\frac{T_p^2}{T_e^2}
=\frac{\bigl(\tfrac{4\pi^2}{GM}\,r_p^3\bigr)}{\bigl(\tfrac{4\pi^2}{GM}\,r_e^3\bigr)}
=\frac{r_p^3}{r_e^3}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\frac{r_p}{r_e}
=\Bigl(\frac{T_p}{T_e}\Bigr)^{2/3}.
\]  
Numerically, with \(T_p=9.5\) d and \(T_e=365\) d,  
