Here is a step-by-step derivation based on the Chapman–Enskog first approximation for a binary gas mixture A–B.

1. Definition  
   The binary mass (or molecular) diffusivity \(D_{AB}\) in a dilute gas is given by  
   \[
     D_{AB}
     = \frac{3}{16\,n\,\sigma_{AB}^2}
       \sqrt{\frac{2\pi k_B T}{\mu_{AB}}}
       \,\frac{1}{\Omega_D(T^*)}
   \]
   where  
   – \(n\) is the total number density,  
   – \(\sigma_{AB}\) is the collision diameter,  
   – \(\mu_{AB} = \dfrac{m_A m_B}{m_A + m_B}\) is the reduced mass,  
   – \(\Omega_D(T^*)\) is the (dimensionless) collision integral, a weak function of the reduced temperature \(T^*\).  

2. Express number density in terms of pressure and temperature  
   \[
     n = \frac{P}{k_B T}\,.
   \]
   Substituting into \(D_{AB}\) gives  
   \[
     D_{AB}
     = \frac{3}{16\,(P/(k_B T))\,\sigma_{AB}^2}
       \sqrt{\frac{2\pi k_B T}{\mu_{AB}}}
       \,\frac{1}{\Omega_D(T^*)}
     = \frac{3\,k_B\,T}{16\,P\,\sigma_{AB}^2}
       \sqrt{\frac{2\pi k_B T}{\mu_{AB}}}
       \frac{1}{\Omega_D(T^*)}\,.
   \]

3. Collecting the \(T\)–dependence  
   \[
     D_{AB}
     = \frac{3}{16\,\sigma_{AB}^2\,\Omega_D(T^*)}
       \sqrt{\frac{2\pi k_B}{\mu_{AB}}}
     \;\frac{(k_B T)^{3/2}}{P}
     \;\propto\;\frac{T^{3/2}}{P}\times\frac{1}{\Omega_D(T^*)}\,.
   \]
   Since \(\Omega_D(T^*)\) varies only slowly with \(T\), one often writes approximately  
   \[
     D_{AB}\;\propto\;\frac{T^{s}}{P}
     \quad\text{with }s\approx1.5\text{–}1.8.
   \]

Final brief answers:

(a) Temperature dependence  
\[
  D_{AB}\;\propto\;\frac{T^{3/2}}{\Omega_D(T^*)}\;\approx\;T^{1.5\text{–}1.8}\,.
\]

(b) Pressure dependence  
\[
  D_{AB}\;\propto\;\frac{1}{P}\,.
\]

Below we use the standard cylindrical‐coordinate formulas  
(9.2)  \[ \nabla \;=\; e_{r}\,\frac{\partial}{\partial r}
  \;+\;\frac{e_{\theta}}{r}\,\frac{\partial}{\partial \theta}
  \;+\;e_{z}\,\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\,, \]  
(9.8)  \[ 
  \nabla\!\cdot\!A
  =\frac1r\frac{\partial (rA_{r})}{\partial r}
  +\frac1r\frac{\partial A_{\theta}}{\partial\theta}
  +\frac{\partial A_{z}}{\partial z}\,, \]  
(9.11) \[
  \nabla\times A
  =\Bigl(\frac1r\frac{\partial A_{z}}{\partial\theta}
           -\frac{\partial (rA_{\theta})}{\partial z}\Bigr)e_{r}
   +\Bigl(\frac{\partial A_{r}}{\partial z}
           -\frac{\partial A_{z}}{\partial r}\Bigr)e_{\theta}
   +\frac1r\Bigl(\frac{\partial (rA_{\theta})}{\partial r}
                -\frac{\partial A_{r}}{\partial\theta}\Bigr)e_{z}\,. 
\]  
Since  
   \(e_{r}\) has components \((A_{r},A_{\theta},A_{z})=(1,0,0)\),  
   \(e_{\theta}\) has \((0,1,0)\),  
we substitute into (9.8),(9.11):

1) ∇·eₙₗ: for \(A=e_{r}\):
\[
   \nabla\cdot e_{r}
   =\frac1r\frac{\partial(r\cdot1)}{\partial r}
    +\frac1r\frac{\partial(0)}{\partial\theta}
    +0
   =\frac1r\;.
\]

2) ∇·eₜₕ: for \(A=e_{\theta}\):
\[
   \nabla\cdot e_{\theta}
   =\frac1r\frac{\partial(r\cdot0)}{\partial r}
    +\frac1r\frac{\partial(1)}{\partial\theta}
    +0
   =0\;.
\]

3) ∇×eₙₗ: for \(A=e_{r}\):
\[
   \nabla\times e_{r}
   =0\,e_{r}+0\,e_{\theta}
     +\frac1r\Bigl(\frac{\partial(r\cdot0)}{\partial r}
                  -\frac{\partial(1)}{\partial\theta}\Bigr)e_{z}
   =0\;.
\]

4) ∇×eₜₕ: for \(A=e_{\theta}\):
\[
   \nabla\times e_{\theta}
   =0\,e_{r}+0\,e_{\theta}
     +\frac1r\Bigl(\frac{\partial(r\cdot1)}{\partial r}
                  -\frac{\partial(0)}{\partial\theta}\Bigr)e_{z}
   =\frac1r\,e_{z}\;.
\]

Final answers (brief):

• \(\nabla\!\cdot e_{r} = \dfrac1r\)  
• \(\nabla\!\cdot e_{\theta} = 0\)  
• \(\nabla\times e_{r} = 0\)  
• \(\nabla\times e_{\theta} = \dfrac1r\,e_{z}\)

